Sorry if this isn't the right place, this is more of a feature suggestion than a bug.

Currently, MonoGame treats Mouse as a separate input mode than Touch.  This certainly makes sense given XNA's history of supporting Mouse on Windows, and Touch on Windows Phone, with no real platform that would have both.

That is, until now, with Windows 8.  Apps/Games on Windows Store are required to support both Mouse and Touch inputs.  Windows has made it easy to support both by normalizing input down into the "Pointer" concept.  This is pervasive in the Windows platforms (XAML, C++, and Web - where Microsoft is pushing Pointer input as a W3C standard).  You can  read about that unified standard here:  http://blogs.msdn.com/b/ie/archive/2012/09/24/towards-interoperable-pointer-events-evolving-input-events-for-multiple-devices.aspx

Given that Win8 apps need to support both, and that there is an existing way of treating them both the same (Pointer) and that many Windows Phone ports will already be wired up to XNA TouchPanel, I think it makes sense to allow the TouchPanel to process Mouse as a virtual touch point.

Since both mouse and touch input comes into MonoGame as Windows Pointer events, this seems very easy to wire up.

In fact, I think it is just a matter of resolving out this filtering in InputEvents.cs:

``` C#
var isTouch = pointerPoint.PointerDevice.PointerDeviceType == PointerDeviceType.Touch;
if (isTouch)
    TouchPanel.AddEvent((int)pointerPoint.PointerId, TouchLocationState.Pressed, pos);
else
{
    // Mouse or stylus event.
    UpdateMouse(pointerPoint);
```

In my own experimenting, simply setting isTouch = true allows my mouse to work as a touch point.  Since Gestures are driven by these touch locations, gestures also now work with the mouse.

This allows me to continue coding my game to TouchPanel, and Mouse will be interpreted as another touch point (with PointerID=1 in windows).

Obviously, real mouse input would stil need to be supported.  There could be a new mode where mouse is treated as touch only (no mouse events), or a mode where mouse is ALSO treated as touch (and still maintains mouse events).  Windows and Internet Explorer always treat mouse as pointer, and maintain the "legacy" mouse events in parallel (so for mouse movements you get both the mouse events and pointer events).

Any thoughts on this?  I'm going to implement support for this in the FourBros fork because we need it to port Taptitude to Windows 8 (Taptitude is a Windows Phone game currently and has no knowledge of Mouse).
